WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:01.968
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.968 --> 00:00:03.444
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.444 --> 00:00:04.920
[CLICKING]

00:00:10.923 --> 00:00:12.840
JONATHAN GRUBER: OK, why
don't we get started?

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:15.590
Since I had some problems
with the end of last lecture,

00:00:15.590 --> 00:00:17.810
I'm going to pick up
right where things

00:00:17.810 --> 00:00:19.590
got a little dicey
in the last lecture,

00:00:19.590 --> 00:00:20.840
and we're going to start over.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:25.070
So we're looking back at figure
7-3, which, if you remember,

00:00:25.070 --> 00:00:28.955
was the cost curves for our cost
function 10 plus 5q squared.

00:00:28.955 --> 00:00:30.620
And you remember
where it came from.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:33.410
This cost function
we derived ourselves

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:36.080
from the production function
and wages and rental rates.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:37.950
We derived this cost function.

00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:39.950
We're now graphing the
cost curves that come out

00:00:39.950 --> 00:00:42.140
of this cost function,
and we're talking

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:43.570
about profit maximization.

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:46.330
And we're talking
about measuring profit.

00:00:46.330 --> 00:00:51.620
So we're talking about
perfect competition.

00:00:51.620 --> 00:00:54.420
And remember, we
said that profits

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:56.650
are revenues minus costs.

00:00:56.650 --> 00:01:00.160
That means the profits
per unit are revenues

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:03.550
per unit minus costs per unit.

00:01:03.550 --> 00:01:08.780
Revenues per unit are price, and
cost per unit is average cost.

00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:13.082
So profits per unit is price
minus the average cost.

00:01:13.082 --> 00:01:14.290
So we just go to the diagram.

00:01:14.290 --> 00:01:16.800
You see the height of
the profit rectangle

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:20.290
is price minus the average cost.

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:21.040
So what do you do?

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.080
You start by finding the point.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.550
So what are your steps here?

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:26.260
Step one is you
find the point where

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.258
price equals marginal cost.

00:01:28.258 --> 00:01:29.800
That gives you your
production level.

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.810
That gives your optimal q star--

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:33.670
we derived that last time--

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:34.900
of 3.

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:38.110
We derived that last time that
you want to optimize the price

00:01:38.110 --> 00:01:39.770
equals marginal cost.

00:01:39.770 --> 00:01:41.590
That gives our q star of 3.

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:45.400
Then at that level, we
compute the average cost.

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:49.420
Average cost at q
of 3 is simply going

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:52.060
to be this cost
function divided by 3--

00:01:52.060 --> 00:02:02.470
so 10 over 3 plus 5q
squared over 3, or just 5q,

00:02:02.470 --> 00:02:04.840
plus 15, OK?

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:10.900
So the average cost at
three is going to be $18.33.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:14.410
That's going to be the average
cost at production of three.

00:02:14.410 --> 00:02:20.710
That means that
the profits we're

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:24.610
making for that third unit,
the profits on our third unit,

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:26.830
is the price--

00:02:26.830 --> 00:02:35.620
profits per unit are the price,
which is a fixed level of 30,

00:02:35.620 --> 00:02:41.370
minus the average
cost, which is $18.33.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:45.300
So profits per
unit equals $11.67.

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:46.390
So that's the profits.

00:02:46.390 --> 00:02:48.430
That's the height
of the rectangle.

00:02:48.430 --> 00:02:51.750
The profits per unit is $11.67.

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:56.190
The price minus the
average cost is $11.67.

00:02:56.190 --> 00:02:59.250
We're selling three units, so
that means our total profit

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:03.720
rectangle is 35, OK?

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:06.180
So our total profits
are 35, which

00:03:06.180 --> 00:03:10.440
is three units at a
profit of $11.67 each.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.540
And that's how we
get that rectangle.

00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:14.900
Questions about that?

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:15.660
OK.

00:03:15.660 --> 00:03:18.730
So now, let's return to
what we did last time.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:25.615
Let's imagine there's
a tax of $10 per unit.

00:03:25.615 --> 00:03:30.730
That would shift the
cost curve to C equals 10

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:33.920
plus 5q squared plus 10q.

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:38.930
Remember, it's a tax
per unit, plus 10q.

00:03:38.930 --> 00:03:42.560
That would mean-- so that is
illustrated in figure 7-4.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:48.850
That means that the marginal
cost curve and the average cost

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:51.160
curve both shift up.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:55.830
Marginal cost is now
equal to 10q plus 10.

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:03.720
We want to set that equal to
the price to get the optimal q,

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:08.490
and you solve this and you
get a new q star equals 2.

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:11.740
So now your optimal
production level is two.

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:15.200
You set your new marginal
cost equal to the price.

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.089
Marginal cost equals price.

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:21.120
Marginal cost equals price at
a new optimal quantity of two.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:22.890
What's the profits there?

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:27.570
Well, once again,
profits per unit

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:30.870
are just price, which is
$30, minus average cost.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:33.240
Well, what's the
average cost at two?

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:35.760
The average cost at two
is going to be 10 over q--

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:37.170
so 5.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:40.290
10 over 2 is 5, OK?

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:47.280
Plus 5q because we're dividing
this by q, 5q, which is 10, OK?

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:51.080
Plus 10, OK?

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:54.590
30 minus 25, which equals 5.

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:58.250
So your profits per unit,
the height of that rectangle,

00:04:58.250 --> 00:05:04.300
has fallen from $11.67 to $5.

00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:06.910
So you're now making
less profit per unit

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:08.950
and you're selling fewer units.

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:10.630
The height of the
rectangle has shrunk.

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:12.213
The width of the
rectangle has shrunk.

00:05:12.213 --> 00:05:17.116
So the total profits have
fallen from $30 to $10.

00:05:17.116 --> 00:05:21.110
You used to make profits of
$11.67 on each of three units.

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:23.960
Now you make profits of
$5 on each of two units.

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:28.940
So that tax has lowered your
profits from $30 to $10, OK?

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:30.150
Question about that?

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:30.650
Yeah.

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:33.720
AUDIENCE: Is that by changing
the cost [INAUDIBLE]??

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:34.970
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yes, exactly.

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:36.690
Because you have a higher cost--

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:38.870
now, it's not just
that your costs change.

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:41.635
Your costs changing fed through
to your production as well.

00:05:41.635 --> 00:05:43.010
So because your
costs change, you

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:44.718
produce at a different
level and you made

00:05:44.718 --> 00:05:48.170
different profit per unit, OK?

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:48.763
All right.

00:05:48.763 --> 00:05:50.180
Now, let's go to
the other point I

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:52.670
tried to cover last time that
I want to get straight on,

00:05:52.670 --> 00:05:55.770
which is the shutdown decision.

00:05:55.770 --> 00:06:00.210
Now remember, we are, in
the short run, shut down.

00:06:00.210 --> 00:06:01.750
We're in the short run.

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.930
In the short run, there's
no entry and exit.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:08.520
The firm can't literally leave,
but it can just produce zero.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.840
That we call the short-run
shutdown decision.

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:13.500
A short-run shutdown decision,
you're still in the market.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.300
You still paid your fixed costs.

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:17.163
You just produce zero.

00:06:17.163 --> 00:06:19.330
That's what we mean by
shutdown, as opposed to exit,

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:21.360
which is literally you
take your toys and leave.

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:22.350
This is you're
still in the market.

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:23.080
You've paid your fixed costs.

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:24.690
You can't go
anywhere-- remember,

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:26.370
those costs are fixed
in the short run--

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:28.700
but you just produce zero.

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:31.520
So now let's ask,
for example, what

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:35.810
happens if the price
suddenly dropped to $10.

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:38.520
Let's say the price
dropped from $30 to $10.

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:41.640
Well, the fundamental
profit-maximization rule

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:43.745
never changes.

00:06:43.745 --> 00:06:45.120
We're not having
the tax anymore.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:47.610
We're back to the
original cost function.

00:06:47.610 --> 00:06:53.720
So original cost function is C
equals 10 plus 5q squared, OK?

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:57.950
So the marginal
cost equals 10q, and

00:06:57.950 --> 00:07:00.440
our profit-maximization
rule does not change.

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:03.050
Our profit-maximization
rule is that price

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:04.800
equals marginal cost.

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:09.090
So we set 10q to 10,
marginal cost equal to price.

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:10.300
$10 is the price.

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:14.480
And we get that the optimal
quantity is now one.

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:16.070
We now want to produce one unit.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:18.430
That's the optimal quantity.

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:21.480
Well, what is our profits
if we produce one unit?

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:27.600
Well, profits equals
revenues, $10, minus costs.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:30.320
Well, what's our cost
if we produce one unit?

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:33.390
10 plus 5, 15.

00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:34.980
So profits are negative 5.

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:41.680
I'm going fast, so jump in if
I get the math wrong here, OK?

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:44.470
Profits are negative 5.

00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:46.470
So you might think that's
terrible, using money.

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:49.500
You should get out
of there, shut down.

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:51.390
But the answer is, as
we discussed last time,

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:54.870
you should not shut down
because shutting down still

00:07:54.870 --> 00:07:57.650
means paying your fixed costs.

00:07:57.650 --> 00:08:00.240
No matter what you do, you
have to pay those fixed costs.

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:03.110
So shutting down means
production of zero.

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:05.390
What are your profits
at a production of zero?

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:07.220
Your profits at a
production of zero

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:12.520
are zero revenues minus
the fixed cost of $10.

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:14.500
If you produce zero,
what's your cost?

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:15.880
Plug 0 in here.

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:18.130
Your costs are still 10.

00:08:18.130 --> 00:08:21.470
So if you produce zero,
your profits are minus 10.

00:08:21.470 --> 00:08:23.560
So you should
continue to sell even

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:25.810
though you're losing money.

00:08:25.810 --> 00:08:27.310
Even though you're
losing money, you

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:29.230
continue to sell that one unit.

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:32.270
You don't go to zero.

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:35.240
Because at zero,
you're even worse off.

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:37.720
This is the key thing about
short-run shutdown decision.

00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:39.090
Yeah?

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:41.715
AUDIENCE: What happens if you're
in a position where, like, you

00:08:41.715 --> 00:08:43.507
are afraid you're going
to keep selling one

00:08:43.507 --> 00:08:45.354
unit the next couple of months?

00:08:45.354 --> 00:08:47.410
JONATHAN GRUBER: Ah, but
that's the key thing.

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:50.410
Once you move to the long run,
you can reoptimize your capital

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:51.542
and you can exit.

00:08:51.542 --> 00:08:53.500
But in the short run,
you've already paid that.

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:56.350
You've already laid down your
blanket, which cost you $10.

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:58.450
You might as well
sell at a loss.

00:08:58.450 --> 00:08:59.980
If you just sell
zero, then you've

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:02.550
laid down your blanket for $10
and gotten nothing out of it,

00:09:02.550 --> 00:09:03.070
OK?

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:04.653
That's the transition
to the long run.

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:11.607
And so basically, that's how
you think about the short run

00:09:11.607 --> 00:09:12.440
versus the long run.

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:14.780
So what do we think
about how this works?

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:16.855
So basically, the
shutdown rule, the way

00:09:16.855 --> 00:09:19.210
you think of the math
of the shutdown rule

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:23.420
is that basically you
only want to shut down

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:27.720
if your revenues are less
than your variable costs

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:29.970
because you got to pay your
fixed cost no matter what.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:30.490
That's done.

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:31.490
You're in the short run.

00:09:31.490 --> 00:09:32.000
That's gone.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:32.510
Forget it.

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:34.310
You laid your blanket
down in the bazaar.

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:35.390
That's done.

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:38.840
So you only want to shut
down if your revenues are

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:41.510
less than your variable costs.

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:43.250
You don't care about
your fixed costs.

00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:44.385
That's done.

00:09:44.385 --> 00:09:46.010
You only shut down
if your revenues are

00:09:46.010 --> 00:09:47.450
less than your variable costs.

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:50.030
Well, that's the same
as saying you only want

00:09:50.030 --> 00:09:52.610
to shut down if your price--

00:09:52.610 --> 00:09:54.860
variable costs are pq--

00:09:54.860 --> 00:09:56.390
I'm sorry, your variable cost.

00:09:56.390 --> 00:09:58.130
You only shut down
if your price are

00:09:58.130 --> 00:10:01.410
less than your average
variable cost--

00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:02.930
so divide by q.

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:05.000
You only shut down
if your price is

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.430
less than your average
variable costs.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:09.660
That's the shutdown rule.

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:12.470
Shut down if the
price you get is less

00:10:12.470 --> 00:10:15.390
than, on average, what
you'll get unit for the units

00:10:15.390 --> 00:10:17.540
you sell.

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:21.313
So in our example,
you never shut down.

00:10:21.313 --> 00:10:21.980
And why is that?

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:23.680
Let's look at the
math of our example.

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:25.960
Well, in our example,
what are variable costs?

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:29.302
The variable cost is 5q squared.

00:10:29.302 --> 00:10:31.510
I'm going to put these down
here so I don't have to--

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:35.710
the variable costs in our
example, variable costs

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:39.120
are 5q squared.

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:41.295
So what are average
variable costs?

00:10:41.295 --> 00:10:41.795
5q.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:50.140
Those are average
variable costs.

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:55.960
Now, remember that you want to
shut down if variable costs are

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.460
greater than the price.

00:10:57.460 --> 00:11:00.550
We can express the
price in terms of q.

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:04.690
Because remember, marginal
cost equals price.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:07.540
So 10q equals p.

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:14.290
So at the optimum, it is always
true that p equals q over 10.

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:17.560
That's a profit-maximizing
condition,

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:19.510
that p equals q over 10.

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:21.940
We can just substitute
that in, and we

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:26.710
have that average variable
costs equals 5 times q.

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:35.010
So average variable costs equals
0.5 times p at the optimum.

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:37.555
Because we know that the optimum
marginal cost equals price,

00:11:37.555 --> 00:11:39.930
we can plug that in and say,
at the optimum, average cost

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.156
is 0.5 times p.

00:11:42.156 --> 00:11:43.092
Yeah?

00:11:43.092 --> 00:11:45.432
AUDIENCE: Do you mean
q equals p over 10?

00:11:45.432 --> 00:11:49.210
JONATHAN GRUBER: q-- let
me see if I got that wrong.

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:50.320
Yes, I'm sorry.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:51.178
q equals p over 10.

00:11:51.178 --> 00:11:51.720
You're right.

00:11:55.328 --> 00:11:57.220
q equals p over 10, my bad.

00:11:57.220 --> 00:11:57.970
Sorry.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:02.950
So the average variable
cost is 0.5 times p.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:04.870
What's the shutdown rule?

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:07.030
The shutdown rule is
that price is less

00:12:07.030 --> 00:12:11.500
than average variable cost or
price is less than 0.5 price,

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.580
which can never be true.

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:16.280
So you'd never shut down
with this cost function.

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:18.610
To say it again,
you only shut down

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:21.718
if price is less than
average variable cost.

00:12:21.718 --> 00:12:24.010
We've computed average variable
cost in terms of price,

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:25.780
and it's 0.5 times price.

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:28.630
Therefore, you never shut down.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:33.790
And you could see this
when we actually go to--

00:12:33.790 --> 00:12:36.420
so you can actually
see this in figure 7-5

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:39.130
when we look at the
firm's supply decision.

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:42.280
So what figure 7-5
does is show you,

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:44.890
at every price,
what the firm wants

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:47.160
to produce in the short run.

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:49.920
At a price of $10, it
wants to produce one.

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:51.680
We showed you that.

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:53.780
At a price of $20, it
wants to produce two.

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.690
At a price of $30, it wants
to produce three, and so on.

00:12:56.690 --> 00:13:00.702
That dash-- that line that runs
from 0, 0 all the way up to 4,

00:13:00.702 --> 00:13:04.980
40, that's the
marginal cost line.

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:07.290
At each point, price
equals marginal cost,

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:10.660
the optimal production decision.

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:13.200
And you never shut down.

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:16.630
As long as price is
positive, you produce.

00:13:16.630 --> 00:13:17.130
Yeah?

00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:21.660
AUDIENCE: So in this case, we
don't set price to 10 minus p?

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:24.550
Because if it's 10,
then [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:25.770
will be higher than 10.

00:13:27.945 --> 00:13:29.070
JONATHAN GRUBER: I'm sorry.

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:30.510
I don't understand.

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:31.748
AUDIENCE: So--

00:13:31.748 --> 00:13:34.290
JONATHAN GRUBER: Price is always
above average variable cost,

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:37.470
so you'd never shut down, right?

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:38.920
That's the shutdown rule.

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:40.670
This can never be true
with this function.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:42.545
Price is forever above
average variable cost.

00:13:42.545 --> 00:13:44.950
You can see that in
