00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:47.100
The price equals
the marginal cost,

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:50.610
and that is always above the
average variable cost, OK?

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:53.117
So the bottom line is
you'd never shut down.

00:13:53.117 --> 00:13:54.450
But here's the other cool thing.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:57.060
After all this confusing
math, guess what this line

00:13:57.060 --> 00:13:59.540
is, this marginal cost line.

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:00.837
What else do we call that?

00:14:00.837 --> 00:14:02.170
That's the supply curve, people.

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:04.220
We just derived
the supply curve.

00:14:04.220 --> 00:14:05.450
What's the supply curve?

00:14:05.450 --> 00:14:08.440
The supply curve
is the relationship

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:10.690
between the price in the
market and the amount

00:14:10.690 --> 00:14:12.460
the producer desires to produce.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:14.710
Well, that's what this
marginal cost curve is.

00:14:14.710 --> 00:14:18.280
So we've just shown you that the
firm's supply curve is simply

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:20.660
its marginal cost curve.

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:24.600
So all you need to know to
derive what a firm's supply

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:28.140
curve looks like is what its
marginal cost curve looks like,

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:29.200
and you're done.

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:33.540
So literally, you take
production plus input prices,

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:35.900
and that gives you
the supply curve.

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:36.450
Why?

00:14:36.450 --> 00:14:37.950
Because production
plus input prices

00:14:37.950 --> 00:14:40.652
gives you the cost function.

00:14:40.652 --> 00:14:42.860
Take the derivative of the
cost function with respect

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:43.340
to quantity.

00:14:43.340 --> 00:14:45.090
That gives you the
marginal cost function.

00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:46.920
That's the supply curve.

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:50.750
So just like I could give you
a utility function and a budget

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:54.080
constraint and you got
the demand curve, here, I

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:56.450
can give you a production
function and input prices

00:14:56.450 --> 00:14:58.490
and it gets the supply curve--

00:14:58.490 --> 00:15:02.710
however, only under
perfect competition, OK?

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:04.770
This is only for the case
of perfect competition.

00:15:04.770 --> 00:15:06.353
That's different
from consumer theory.

00:15:06.353 --> 00:15:07.880
That was an everywhere rule.

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:10.400
Because I've given you an
extra constraint, which

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:12.020
is a constraint on
the market, I've

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.670
allowed you to derive the
supply curve just like we easily

00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:17.000
derived the demand curve.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.830
So we have now derived
a firm's supply curve.

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:24.420
Questions about that?

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:25.880
So let's go back one more time.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:30.100
Just like if I give you on,
say, a problem set or an exam

00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:32.060
a utility function and
a budget constraint,

00:15:32.060 --> 00:15:34.670
you should be able to
draw a demand curve.

00:15:34.670 --> 00:15:39.200
If I give you a production
function and input prices

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:41.903
and I tell you you're
in perfect competition,

00:15:41.903 --> 00:15:43.820
then you should be able
to draw a supply curve

00:15:43.820 --> 00:15:47.490
because it's just the
marginal cost curve, OK?

00:15:47.490 --> 00:15:50.922
Now, that's the
firm's supply curve.

00:15:50.922 --> 00:15:52.630
What we care about,
actually, in the end,

00:15:52.630 --> 00:15:54.820
is the market
supply curve, right?

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:56.038
I've been doing little q.

00:15:56.038 --> 00:15:58.330
We care about big Q. That's
what I drew in the lecture,

00:15:58.330 --> 00:16:00.040
was a big Q diagram.

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:01.640
So how do we get there?

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:04.840
Well, all you do to
get the market supply

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:09.010
is to horizontally sum
each firm's supply.

00:16:09.010 --> 00:16:12.430
So we can see that
in figure 7-7, OK?

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:16.480
What figure 7-7 does is take
multiple identical firms

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:18.050
and put them in the market.

00:16:18.050 --> 00:16:21.480
So for example, if there's
one firm in the market,

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:24.440
the supply curve is
what we just drew.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:26.360
At a price of $10, you get 10.

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:28.310
At a price of $10, you get one.

00:16:28.310 --> 00:16:31.370
At a price of $30,
you get three.

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:34.340
Now let's add a
second identical firm.

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:36.980
Well, that firm
behaves the same way.

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:39.240
At a price of $10,
it produces one.

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:41.630
And at a price of $30,
it produces three.

00:16:41.630 --> 00:16:44.960
So the market now suddenly
has twice as much.

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:46.680
At a price of $10, it has two.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:48.650
At a price of $30, it has six.

00:16:48.650 --> 00:16:50.090
Now let's add a third firm.

00:16:50.090 --> 00:16:51.612
It behaves the same way.

00:16:51.612 --> 00:16:53.070
At a price of $10,
it produces one.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:54.800
At a price of $3,
it produces three.

00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:59.360
So each additional firm
you add just literally

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:00.950
shifts the supply curve down.

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:06.980
So in other words, the point
is that a market supply curve,

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:10.130
as you add more and more
firms, the market supply curve

00:17:10.130 --> 00:17:13.310
is always more elastic
than the firm's supply

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:17.089
curve because any
given increase in price

00:17:17.089 --> 00:17:20.270
calls for, from each firm,
an increase in quantity.

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:21.723
As long as there's
multiple firms,

00:17:21.723 --> 00:17:23.390
that means a flatter
market supply curve

00:17:23.390 --> 00:17:24.515
than a firm's supply curve.

00:17:26.785 --> 00:17:28.660
So that's how we get
the market supply curve.

00:17:28.660 --> 00:17:30.520
We solve for the
firm's supply curve.

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:32.650
We then just horizontally
sum it over the number

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:34.690
of firms in the market.

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:37.330
Get the firm supply curve,
horizontally sum, OK?

00:17:37.330 --> 00:17:39.800
Questions about that?

00:17:39.800 --> 00:17:43.500
Now, now we have
everything we need

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:46.740
to go back to the first
lecture, back to the future,

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:48.210
back to the first lecture.

00:17:48.210 --> 00:17:52.200
And we can actually get
to market equilibrium.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:54.330
In the first lecture,
we started with a supply

00:17:54.330 --> 00:17:56.280
curve and a demand curve
and got equilibrium.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:58.488
Well, we derived the demand
curve a few lectures ago.

00:17:58.488 --> 00:18:00.100
We've just derived
the supply curve.

00:18:00.100 --> 00:18:02.187
So let's do short-run
equilibrium.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:08.760
Let's do short-run
equilibrium, OK?

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:12.910
Now, the key thing is that--

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:15.180
so how do we do
short-run equilibrium?

00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:16.630
Let's go through the steps.

00:18:16.630 --> 00:18:20.310
Step one, each firm picks
a fixed amount of capital

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:23.120
it's going to have
in the short run.

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:26.840
So each firm has a K bar.

00:18:26.840 --> 00:18:30.430
And based on that, it has
a production function.

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:32.690
Each firm has a
production function,

00:18:32.690 --> 00:18:42.140
q equals f of k, K bar, L.
And we have some input prices.

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:45.060
We have some w and some r.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:48.940
Taken together, we can use
those to create a cost function,

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:50.820
which, in our example,
was C equals 10

00:18:50.820 --> 00:18:54.740
plus 5q squared, step one.

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:55.390
Step two.

00:19:00.390 --> 00:19:04.650
Step two, based on this, we can
get optimal production levels

00:19:04.650 --> 00:19:06.900
from the fundamental
profit-maximization rule,

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:10.360
MC equals p.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:17.090
So this yields-- so here,
we say 10q equals p.

00:19:17.090 --> 00:19:19.980
And this yields
a supply function

00:19:19.980 --> 00:19:25.858
which is q equals p over 10,
and that's our supply curve.

00:19:25.858 --> 00:19:27.650
That's what I drew
here. q equals p over 10

00:19:27.650 --> 00:19:28.840
is the firm's supply curve.

00:19:31.810 --> 00:19:33.055
That's step two.

00:19:33.055 --> 00:19:36.590
Step three is to create
a market supply curve.

00:19:36.590 --> 00:19:38.590
Well, let's say there's
six firms in the market.

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:39.880
I'm just pulling
