00:23:21.312 --> 00:23:24.810
OK, so now let's ask where
the hell six comes from.

00:23:27.320 --> 00:23:30.110
And where six comes
from is the fact--

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:36.700
where six comes from
is from the long run.

00:23:36.700 --> 00:23:46.552
So now we get to
long-run competition,

00:23:46.552 --> 00:23:48.010
which is, in the
short run, there's

00:23:48.010 --> 00:23:49.750
a certain number of
firms in the market.

00:23:49.750 --> 00:23:51.218
But where those firms come from?

00:23:51.218 --> 00:23:53.260
Well, they come from the
fact that each short run

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:57.140
is a repeated exercise
that makes up the long run.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:24:01.090
So in the long run, perfect
competition in the long run

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:03.370
looks just like perfect
competition in the short run--

00:24:03.370 --> 00:24:07.780
full information, no
transaction cost, lots of firms,

00:24:07.780 --> 00:24:09.160
with one difference.

00:24:09.160 --> 00:24:12.100
We're now going to
allow entry and exit.

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:14.500
Nothing else is going to
change in the short run

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:17.170
except we're now going
to allow entry and exit.

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:22.950
So now, what-- and
one other thing.

00:24:22.950 --> 00:24:23.450
I'm sorry.

00:24:23.450 --> 00:24:25.070
One other thing changes.

00:24:25.070 --> 00:24:29.440
Since all costs are variable,
there's no shutdown decision.

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:31.660
There's no issue of
this shutdown rule.

00:24:31.660 --> 00:24:33.440
There's no more fixed costs.

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:35.850
So if you lose money, in
the long run, you shut down.

00:24:35.850 --> 00:24:37.600
So all you have to
worry about is profits.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.490
You don't have to worry
about this extra shut--

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:41.680
so in the short run, we had
an extra shutdown condition.

00:24:41.680 --> 00:24:42.730
You don't worry about
that in the long run.

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:44.770
You just worry about if you're
making money or losing money.

00:24:44.770 --> 00:24:46.895
In the long run, if you're
making money, you're in.

00:24:46.895 --> 00:24:49.230
If you're losing
money, you're out.

00:24:49.230 --> 00:24:52.670
So now let's ask
how that pins down

00:24:52.670 --> 00:24:55.680
the number of firms
in the market.

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:58.157
This is complicated, so the
best way to do it, I think,

00:24:58.157 --> 00:24:58.740
is an example.

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:04.435
And think about our--

00:25:04.435 --> 00:25:06.060
the fundamental rule
I want you to keep

00:25:06.060 --> 00:25:07.977
in mind-- and the example
gives you this rule.

00:25:07.977 --> 00:25:12.180
The simple rule is if there's
profits to be made, you enter.

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:18.080
If there's losses, you exit.

00:25:18.080 --> 00:25:23.280
And these two things together
imply the fundamental rule

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:26.340
of competitive equilibrium--
that in the long run,

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:27.480
profits are zero.

