It can take hours to
recover from this.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:00.570
Competition forces
cost minimization.

00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:01.260
Why?

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:04.050
Because competition
forces each firm

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:06.990
to produce where price
equals marginal cost,

00:37:06.990 --> 00:37:09.960
and it forces entry and
exit until marginal cost

00:37:09.960 --> 00:37:11.950
equals average cost.

00:37:11.950 --> 00:37:14.280
Therefore, it forces
each firm to produce

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:16.230
at the most efficient
point, which

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:18.353
is where marginal cost
equals average cost,

00:37:18.353 --> 00:37:19.770
because that is
the point at where

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:22.260
average cost is minimized.

00:37:22.260 --> 00:37:24.830
So under competition,
in the long run,

00:37:24.830 --> 00:37:27.080
every firm is cost-minimizing.

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:31.370
They're producing the minimum
of their average costs.

00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:34.550
And therefore, the
supply curve is elastic,

00:37:34.550 --> 00:37:38.150
and it's defined purely by
the minimum of average costs.

00:37:38.150 --> 00:37:39.950
That is, if you know--

00:37:39.950 --> 00:37:41.370
here's a cheat.

00:37:41.370 --> 00:37:44.630
If you know you're in a
perfectly competitive market

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:49.442
and I give you a cost
function, then you know--

00:37:49.442 --> 00:37:51.400
I guess you still need
the demand function too.

00:37:51.400 --> 00:37:54.693
If I give a cost function
and a demand function,

00:37:54.693 --> 00:37:56.610
you know you don't need
to know how many firms

00:37:56.610 --> 00:37:57.420
are going to be in the market.

00:37:57.420 --> 00:37:59.070
You don't need to know little n.

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:01.685
You know, in the long run,
profits are going to be zero.

00:38:01.685 --> 00:38:03.060
So long run, firms
are just going

00:38:03.060 --> 00:38:06.460
to produce at the
minimum of average cost.

00:38:06.460 --> 00:38:08.460
You find that, use the
demand to find the price,

00:38:08.460 --> 00:38:11.010
and you're done, OK?

00:38:11.010 --> 00:38:16.620
So competition leads
to cost minimization.

00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:19.360
Questions about that?

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:20.390
OK.

00:38:20.390 --> 00:38:24.580
Now, you're all thinking,
well, wait a second.

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:26.220
We've got rich
parents, many of us who

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:28.688
make money in these businesses.

00:38:28.688 --> 00:38:29.730
I don't see zero profits.

00:38:29.730 --> 00:38:32.310
There's a stock market
that's been booming.

00:38:32.310 --> 00:38:33.990
Where's the zero profits, buddy?

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:36.580
I don't see zero profits.

00:38:36.580 --> 00:38:39.640
Well, the answer is twofold.

00:38:39.640 --> 00:38:42.330
First of all, remember,
firms can make money

00:38:42.330 --> 00:38:44.690
in the short run in this model.

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:46.440
But that doesn't explain
the stock market.

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:48.732
The stock market's supposed
to be forward-looking-- not

00:38:48.732 --> 00:38:50.590
months, but years and decades.

00:38:50.590 --> 00:38:53.190
So firms-- really,
long run profit's zero.

00:38:53.190 --> 00:38:55.650
Why would stocks be expensive?

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:57.840
Why would people want to
invest in these companies?

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:01.190
And the answer is because these
assumptions are unrealistic--

00:39:01.190 --> 00:39:04.160
that this is an extreme
version of the model that

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:06.530
delivers some nice
intuition, but doesn't

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:07.677
apply to the real world.

00:39:07.677 --> 00:39:09.260
So I want to take
the last few minutes

00:39:09.260 --> 00:39:11.510
to talk about the
assumptions that we've

00:39:11.510 --> 00:39:13.660
made that don't really
work in the real world

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:14.660
to make this model work.

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:16.180
It doesn't mean the
model's invalid.

00:39:16.180 --> 00:39:17.880
We learn a huge amount.

00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:19.430
And the key lesson
from this model

00:39:19.430 --> 00:39:23.420
is competition pushes you
towards cost minimization.

00:39:23.420 --> 00:39:28.230
Always think about these models
as not delivering a level

00:39:28.230 --> 00:39:30.810
truth, but a directional truth.

00:39:30.810 --> 00:39:33.870
The directional lesson is this
is why competition forces firms

00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:37.400
towards cost minimization,
but firms won't actually

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:39.740
necessarily get to zero profits.

00:39:39.740 --> 00:39:43.070
And there's at least
three complications.

00:39:43.070 --> 00:39:45.290
The first one is limited entry.

00:39:48.850 --> 00:39:54.530
I assumed that firms could
costlessly enter and exit

00:39:54.530 --> 00:39:57.460
in this market.

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:02.080
But in fact, that might be
hard because, in reality, we

00:40:02.080 --> 00:40:05.920
have sunk costs, which I
talked about last time.

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:09.340
We have sunk costs--
or two times ago--

00:40:09.340 --> 00:40:12.780
costs which, once paid,
can never be recovered.

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:14.400
And therefore, firms
might say, look,

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:15.900
I don't want to get
into this market

00:40:15.900 --> 00:40:17.983
because it's not like I
can get my fixed cost back

00:40:17.983 --> 00:40:19.540
out next period.

00:40:19.540 --> 00:40:21.510
So if my fixed costs
are building a building,

00:40:21.510 --> 00:40:24.000
next period, I can just sell
that building to someone else.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:25.920
But my fixed costs are
going to med school.

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:28.990
I can't sell that
med school degree.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:31.150
Therefore, if doctors aren't
going to be profitable

00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:33.608
in the long run-- there'll be
zero profit in the long run--

00:40:33.608 --> 00:40:35.200
I'm going to go be
a lawyer instead.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:37.270
There are sunk costs,
and those sunk costs

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:39.970
create what we call
barriers to entry.

00:40:44.510 --> 00:40:47.180
There are barriers to
entry that come from costs

00:40:47.180 --> 00:40:50.570
that are sunk in the long run--

00:40:50.570 --> 00:40:51.530
med schools.

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:55.160
But there are other sorts
of barriers to entry.

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:57.600
Take our vendor market.

00:40:57.600 --> 00:40:59.850
Even in vendor markets,
they're not perfectly elastic.

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:00.800
One barrier to
entry could be they

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:03.217
could come in the middle of
the night and steal your stuff

00:41:03.217 --> 00:41:05.810
and beat you up if you
tried to enter the market.

00:41:05.810 --> 00:41:09.560
There's lots of reasons
why entry and exit is not

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:11.840
costless and easy.

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:13.670
There's lots of
barriers to entry.

00:41:13.670 --> 00:41:17.840
Once there's a barrier to
entry, this graph goes away.

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:19.270
Because go back to figure 8-1.

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:23.870
In the second
short-run equilibrium,

00:41:23.870 --> 00:41:26.750
we've got these small
profits, this small, dark gray

00:41:26.750 --> 00:41:29.270
rectangle, right?

00:41:29.270 --> 00:41:31.880
I then told you another firm
would enter and squeeze those

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:35.637
away, but another firm
will enter only if what?

00:41:35.637 --> 00:41:37.970
Only under what-- somebody
raise their hand and tell me.

00:41:37.970 --> 00:41:41.993
Under what condition would
that third firm enter?

00:41:41.993 --> 00:41:42.955
Yeah?

00:41:42.955 --> 00:41:44.880
AUDIENCE: Profits are
greater than zero.

00:41:44.880 --> 00:41:47.430
JONATHAN GRUBER: No, not
profits are greater than zero.

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:48.630
In the model, that was true.

00:41:48.630 --> 00:41:50.658
But in reality,
what has to be true?

00:41:50.658 --> 00:41:52.200
Profits have to be
greater than what?

00:41:52.200 --> 00:41:53.613
AUDIENCE: Sunk cost.

00:41:53.613 --> 00:41:54.780
JONATHAN GRUBER: Sunk costs.

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:56.000
Raise your hand, people.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:56.940
I'm going to give you
credit because you

00:41:56.940 --> 00:41:59.315
raised your hand regardless
of who yelled out the answer.

00:41:59.315 --> 00:42:00.590
I'll assume you were right.

00:42:00.590 --> 00:42:01.560
Sunk costs.

00:42:01.560 --> 00:42:05.370
Profits have to be greater
than the barriers to entry.

00:42:05.370 --> 00:42:07.090
So in the short run,
you enter if profits

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:08.007
are greater than zero.

00:42:08.007 --> 00:42:10.530
In the long run, you
only enter if profits

00:42:10.530 --> 00:42:14.930
are greater than the barriers to
entry, which might not be true.

00:42:14.930 --> 00:42:18.220
There's always some
cost to starting a firm.

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:20.440
So profits will never
really go to zero.

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:23.980
They'll only go down to
the barriers to entry.

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:27.090
So that's problem one.

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:30.450
Problem two with this
model, problem two

00:42:30.450 --> 00:42:32.970
is firms may differ.

00:42:32.970 --> 00:42:36.000
I've assumed-- and this
was raised in one question.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.500
I've assumed
identical firms here.

00:42:38.500 --> 00:42:40.440
But in fact, firms differ.

00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:42.750
And in particular,
different firms

00:42:42.750 --> 00:42:45.740
have different cost functions.

00:42:45.740 --> 00:42:47.780
And with different
cost functions,

00:42:47.780 --> 00:42:52.330
you can get some firms
making long-run profits.

00:42:52.330 --> 00:42:58.320
So for example, let's
consider, in figure 8-4,

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:00.870
the long-run market
supply for cotton.

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:04.410
This is from a textbook example.

00:43:04.410 --> 00:43:07.440
And this is from
estimates that people

00:43:07.440 --> 00:43:12.240
have made of the minimum
average cost of producing cotton

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:14.280
by country.

00:43:14.280 --> 00:43:17.278
So in other words, this is old
now, but it doesn't matter.

00:43:17.278 --> 00:43:18.570
The country names don't matter.

00:43:18.570 --> 00:43:19.920
The example's what matters.

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:21.750
In the period of time
this study was done,

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.330
the cheapest place to
produce cotton was Pakistan.

00:43:24.330 --> 00:43:29.230
You produce cotton in
Pakistan for $0.71 per--

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:34.200
I don't know-- kilogram,
$0.71 per kilogram, OK?

00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:37.480
However, that was only
for a certain amount.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:40.717
At some point, Pakistan
ran out of cheap cotton

00:43:40.717 --> 00:43:42.550
and they had to start
producing cotton using

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:43.727
more expensive methods.

00:43:43.727 --> 00:43:46.060
Remember, marginal cost, at
some point, has to slope up.

00:43:46.060 --> 00:43:47.890
So the point is
marginal cost was flat

00:43:47.890 --> 00:43:51.160
for a while in Pakistan,
then has to slope up.

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:55.000
And suddenly, it becomes cheaper
to produce cotton in Argentina

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.728
at $1.08.

00:43:57.728 --> 00:44:00.145
And then it becomes cheaper
to produce cotton in Australia

00:44:00.145 --> 00:44:01.070
at $1.15.

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:03.408
And eventually, if the
price gets to $1.56,

00:44:03.408 --> 00:44:05.200
it's finally cheap
enough to produce cotton

00:44:05.200 --> 00:44:07.410
in the United States.

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:09.870
The point is these
flat segments represent

00:44:09.870 --> 00:44:12.060
the minimum average
cost in each country.

00:44:12.060 --> 00:44:13.920
It's just, instead
of making it a point,

00:44:13.920 --> 00:44:15.712
there's an amount of
production they can do

00:44:15.712 --> 00:44:18.130
with that minimum average cost.

00:44:18.130 --> 00:44:21.270
Now, let's say world
demand for cotton

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:24.540
was 1 billion
kilograms per year.

00:44:24.540 --> 00:44:27.900
Then what would happen
would be what I taught.

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:29.970
You would have Pakistan--

00:44:29.970 --> 00:44:34.230
competitors in Pakistan would
compete, driving profits down

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:35.610
to zero.

00:44:35.610 --> 00:44:39.940
And price would be
$0.71 per kilogram.

00:44:39.940 --> 00:44:42.720
Now let's say, however,
demand for cotton

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:45.710
is 5 billion kilograms per year.

00:44:45.710 --> 00:44:48.700
Well, now, that intersects
this supply curve.

00:44:48.700 --> 00:44:50.030
This is the world supply curve.

00:44:50.030 --> 00:44:54.570
There's the supply
curve at $1.71.

00:44:54.570 --> 00:44:59.160
So now, US producers
are making zero profits

00:44:59.160 --> 00:45:00.690
because their
marginal cost's $1.71.

00:45:00.690 --> 00:45:02.250
The price is $1.71.

00:45:02.250 --> 00:45:05.230
But what about
producers in Pakistan?

00:45:05.230 --> 00:45:07.190
They still make cotton.

00:45:07.190 --> 00:45:10.410
They make the first
almost 2 billion kilos.

00:45:10.410 --> 00:45:15.420
But they're selling at $1.71,
and it's costing them $0.71.

00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:18.400
So they just made profits.

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:23.830
The point is that if there are
firms which have rising costs

00:45:23.830 --> 00:45:26.150
and demand is high enough
that the high-cost firms are

00:45:26.150 --> 00:45:28.090
actually producing,
that higher price means

00:45:28.090 --> 00:45:30.010
profits for the low-cost firm.

00:45:30.010 --> 00:45:30.610
Yeah?

00:45:30.610 --> 00:45:34.503
AUDIENCE: Would this increase
the price variable in Pakistan?

00:45:34.503 --> 00:45:35.920
JONATHAN GRUBER:
You could imagine

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:38.410
those profits could
then have a feedback

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:40.300
effect in asset markets.

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:42.850
And you could imagine the long
run, in the very, very, very

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:45.373
long run, as people
buy land, that

00:45:45.373 --> 00:45:46.540
could dissipate the profits.

00:45:46.540 --> 00:45:47.373
That's a good point.

00:45:47.373 --> 00:45:48.730
We'll come back to that.

00:45:48.730 --> 00:45:51.400
But no, that's
very long run, OK?

00:45:51.400 --> 00:45:54.298
But for now, people have
their land in Pakistan,

00:45:54.298 --> 00:45:55.840
and they're making
their money on it.

00:45:55.840 --> 00:45:58.120
And so that becomes
long-run profits.

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:02.380
So long-run profits can come
from heterogeneous costs.

00:46:02.380 --> 00:46:05.230
If some firms are
particularly efficient

00:46:05.230 --> 00:46:09.870
in a multimarket firm,
those firms can make money.

00:46:09.870 --> 00:46:14.250
That's a second feature.

00:46:14.250 --> 00:46:17.800
Now, the third feature
is, in some sense,

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:23.840
the most interesting, which is
input prices may not be fixed.

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:29.230
And in fact, input
prices, input prices--

00:46:29.230 --> 00:46:29.730
ah.

00:46:34.230 --> 00:46:42.410
Input may have an
upward-sloping supply.

00:46:42.410 --> 00:46:45.277
There could be an upward-sloping
supply for inputs.

00:46:45.277 --> 00:46:47.360
We've assumed input prices
are, everywhere, fixed,

00:46:47.360 --> 00:46:48.780
but that's not true.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:51.540
And in a few lectures, we'll
come and teach you about that.

00:46:51.540 --> 00:46:53.900
But for now, let's
recognize that inputs may

00:46:53.900 --> 00:46:55.770
have an upward-sloping supply.

00:46:55.770 --> 00:46:58.963
So let's go through that for a
couple minutes before we stop.

00:46:58.963 --> 00:47:00.380
Let's take a market
in figure 8-5.

00:47:03.730 --> 00:47:06.847
This is the market for labor.

00:47:06.847 --> 00:47:08.680
Now, we've only been
doing markets for goods

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:10.805
so far in this course, and
I'm sort of shortcutting

00:47:10.805 --> 00:47:11.680
by jumping to here.

00:47:11.680 --> 00:47:13.540
We'll spend a lot more
time on this graph.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:17.770
But the bottom line is this is
a graph of the amount of labor

00:47:17.770 --> 00:47:19.300
supply to the market.

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:22.227
In this graph, people
are now the suppliers

00:47:22.227 --> 00:47:23.560
because they're supplying labor.

00:47:23.560 --> 00:47:25.300
Firms are the demanders.

00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:27.190
They're demanding labor.

00:47:27.190 --> 00:47:29.320
So what happens is you
have supply curve of labor,

00:47:29.320 --> 00:47:30.862
and let's assume
it's upward sloping.

00:47:30.862 --> 00:47:33.400
What I mean by that is
as the wage goes up,

00:47:33.400 --> 00:47:35.557
people want to work harder.

00:47:35.557 --> 00:47:37.390
You want to work harder
as the wage goes up.

00:47:37.390 --> 00:47:38.770
So it's an
upward-sloping supply.

00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:41.260
It makes sense, right?

00:47:41.260 --> 00:47:43.240
Upward-sloping supply of labor.

00:47:43.240 --> 00:47:47.560
Now let's imagine a firm
suddenly wants to produce more.

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:49.960
They used to produce little q1.

00:47:49.960 --> 00:47:52.430
Now they want to
produce little q2.

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:55.280
To do so, they
need more workers.

00:47:55.280 --> 00:47:59.460
That represents a shift out
in the demand for workers.

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:02.680
With upward-sloping
supply, what does that do?

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:04.720
Raises the wage.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:07.428
If you want more workers,
you've got to pay them more.

00:48:07.428 --> 00:48:08.470
We didn't do that before.

00:48:08.470 --> 00:48:10.940
We assumed W was a constant.

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:13.940
But imagine if, to produce
more, you have to pay more.

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:15.080
What does that do?

00:48:15.080 --> 00:48:17.900
Well, you see that
in figure 8-6.

00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:21.560
Now, I used to produce--
the market equilibrium used

00:48:21.560 --> 00:48:28.240
to be at point E1 with n1
firms producing little q1.

00:48:28.240 --> 00:48:30.110
So that point big E1--

00:48:30.110 --> 00:48:33.020
biggie, big comma E1--

00:48:33.020 --> 00:48:35.090
is little n1.

00:48:35.090 --> 00:48:40.220
There was n firms producing
little q1 units per firm.

00:48:40.220 --> 00:48:43.120
And they were making
these profits.

00:48:43.120 --> 00:48:47.780
Their profits were where
price equaled marginal cost 1,

00:48:47.780 --> 00:48:49.520
now shifting to the left.

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:52.310
p equals marginal
cost one at little e1.

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:55.110
So they were producing
where marginal cost equaled

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:56.730
average cost.

00:48:56.730 --> 00:49:00.620
So little q1 at price
p1 meant that firms

00:49:00.620 --> 00:49:05.090
producing at little e1, which
was the zero-profit point, OK?

00:49:05.090 --> 00:49:07.220
Now what happens?

00:49:07.220 --> 00:49:08.840
Now the firm wants
to produce more.

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:09.500
Demand goes up.

00:49:09.500 --> 00:49:10.790
Firm wants to produce more.

00:49:10.790 --> 00:49:12.772
It wants to produce q2.

00:49:12.772 --> 00:49:15.560
You have a new long-run
equilibrium with n2 firms

00:49:15.560 --> 00:49:16.960
producing q2.

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:21.520
Well, in that case, now
if you want to produce q2,

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:23.830
you're going to have
to pay a higher wage.

00:49:23.830 --> 00:49:28.540
A higher wage means a higher
marginal average cost.

00:49:28.540 --> 00:49:30.370
Higher marginal
average cost means

00:49:30.370 --> 00:49:34.410
that you're now producing
at a higher price

00:49:34.410 --> 00:49:36.450
and, therefore, the supply
curve slopes upward.

00:49:39.210 --> 00:49:40.607
Now, this is very different.

00:49:40.607 --> 00:49:41.690
One thing to think about--

00:49:41.690 --> 00:49:42.357
I'll let you go.

00:49:42.357 --> 00:49:44.600
One last thing to think,
think about the difference

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:47.160
between this third case
and the other two cases.

00:49:47.160 --> 00:49:50.720
In the other two cases,
firms made profits.

00:49:50.720 --> 00:49:54.310
In this case, firms
still don't make profits.

00:49:54.310 --> 00:49:55.860
So notice that
profit's still zero,

00:49:55.860 --> 00:49:58.225
but the supply curve's
upward sloping.

00:49:58.225 --> 00:49:59.850
So you don't need
positive profits have

00:49:59.850 --> 00:50:01.630
an upward-sloping supply curve.

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:02.580
So let's stop there.

00:50:02.580 --> 00:50:04.530
I've given you a
lot to think about.

00:50:04.530 --> 00:50:06.330
And we will come
back and talk more

00:50:06.330 --> 00:50:09.230
about this stuff on Wednesday.